Package io.honeycomb.libhoney

Class Metrics

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.honeycomb.libhoney.Metrics

  • public final class Metrics
extends Object
    Records measurements of elapsed time (in nanoseconds) for an event that has been submitted to the HoneyClient. These metrics are accessible by registering a ResponseObserver and consuming a response for an event. The measurements may be incomplete, in which case a value of -1 will be returned. For example, an event that was not sampled will not contain any measurements.

      • getQueueDuration

        public long getQueueDuration​()
        Get the elapsed time from the event being accepted by the HoneyClient until the event was submitted to the HTTP client as part of a batch request. Under normal circumstances this should be close or under the configured TransportOptions.Builder.setBatchTimeoutMillis(long), but if the HTTP client is overloaded it's backpressure might lead to an increase in this measurement.
        Returns:
        the total elapsed time in nanoseconds, or -1 if the metric is not available.
        See Also:
        TransportOptions.Builder.setBatchSize(int), TransportOptions.Builder.setBatchTimeoutMillis(long), TransportOptions.Builder.setQueueCapacity(int)

      • getTotalDuration

        public long getTotalDuration​()
        Get the total elapsed time from the event being accepted by the HoneyClient until the server responded to the HTTP request containing the event. This is equal to getQueueDuration() plus getHttpRequestDuration() (on the assumption that both metrics are available).
        Returns:
        the total elapsed time in nanoseconds, or -1 if the metric is not available.

      • getHttpRequestDuration

        public long getHttpRequestDuration​()
        Get the time it took for the server to respond to the batch request. The timer starts from when the event's batch is handed to the HTTP client up to when it responds with a status code. This means that exceptional completions of the request (e.g. due to networking issues) are not measured.

        A high duration could be an indication of network latency, but also of the HTTP client being overloaded (i.e. if it takes a long time for the event's batch to lease an HTTP connection).

        Returns:
        the total elapsed time in nanoseconds that the HTTP request to the server took to process, or -1 if the metric is not available.
        See Also:
        TransportOptions.Builder.setMaxConnectionsPerApiHost(int), TransportOptions.Builder.setMaxConnectionsPerApiHost(int), TransportOptions.Builder.setMaximumPendingBatchRequests(int)
